<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="46" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="3.[2058,2652,1362,1789]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2059,2214,1362,1395]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Yepes, 1933" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[2224,2595,1362,1395]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasypodidae" genus="Dasypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cingulata" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" species="mazzai">Dasypus mazzai Yepes, 1933</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation pageId="3" pageNumber="46">
Tabacal, Oran Department, Salta, Argentina. Identity of 
<taxonomicName authority="Yepes, 1933" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[2222,2355,1441,1474]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasypodidae" genus="Dasypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cingulata" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" species="mazzai">D. mazzai</taxonomicName>
</materialsCitation>
has been controver- sial, with some claiming the type specimen was actually a young 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[2360,2575,1520,1553]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasypodidae" genus="Dasypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cingulata" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="novemcinctus">D. novemcinctus</taxonomicName>
. S. F. Vizcaino in 1995 proposed that a separate species should be recognized and named it 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vizcaino" authorityYear="1995" box="[2085,2196,1638,1671]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasypodidae" genus="Dasypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cingulata" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="yepesi">D. yepesi</taxonomicName>
. A. Feijo and P. Cordeiro-Estrela in 2014 presented evidence that this new species was in fact the same as that originally identified by J. Yepes in 1933, thus
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[1443,2650,1794,2538]" box="[1446,2112,1794,1827]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">
making 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yepes" authorityYear="1933" box="[1560,1689,1794,1827]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasypodidae" genus="Dasypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cingulata" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mazzai">D. mazzai</taxonomicName>
the correct name. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="46" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" targetBox="[1443,2035,1366,1780]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[1443,2650,1794,2538]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1446,1622,1834,1867]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from Jujuy and Salta provinces, NW Argentina. This limited range might be due to the fact that only nine locality records are available.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="46" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[1443,2650,1794,2538]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1445,1699,1921,1946]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body ¢.310 mm, tail 180-230 mm, ear 36-38 mm; weight c.2.2-5 kg. The Yungas Lesser Long-nosed Armadillo is an intermediate-sized species of long-nosed armadillos, with body proportions similar to, but somewhat larger than, those of the Southern Long-nosed Armadillo (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Desmarest" authorityYear="1804" box="[2113,2270,2031,2064]" class="Mammalia" family="Dasypodidae" genus="Dasypus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cingulata" pageId="3" pageNumber="46" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hybridus">D. hybridus</taxonomicName>
). It normally has 7-8 movable bands on carapace and relatively long tail and ears.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="46" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[1443,2650,1794,2538]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1445,1556,2110,2143]" pageId="3" pageNumber="46">Habitat.</emphasis>
Typically, Yungas forest at elevations up to 1800 m and also in more xeric habitats (Chaco) at elevations of ¢.440 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
